documentation.description:
This component uses token authentication to interact with the Tableau API.
To generate a token:

-   Log in to **Tableau**
-   Click the user icon in the top right, and click **My Account Settings**
-   Under **Personal Access Tokens**, type in a **Token Name** and select **Create new token**.
    Take note of the **Token Name** and **Token Secret** - you'll enter those into Prismatic in a moment
-   Look at your Tableau URL.
    It'll look like `https://10ay.online.tableau.com/#/site/MarketingTeam/workbooks`.
    You'll use the `10ay.online.tableau.com` portion as your **Host Name**, and `MarketingTeam` as your **Site ID**.

Now, add a Tableau step to Prismatic.
This will automatically create a Tableau connection config variable.
Fill in the config variable with the **Token Name**, **Token Secret**, **Host Name** and **Site ID** that you noted above.

For additional information regarding authentication, please refer to the [Tableau docs](https://help.tableau.com/current/api/rest_api/en-us/REST/rest_api_concepts_auth.htm).

inputs.comments: The maximum amount of time the client will await a response.

inputs.comments: This flag will enable debugging and logging of the action's web request.

inputs.comments: If you are calling this method to commit a file that was uploaded in parts, this value contains the upload session ID that was generated by a call to Initiate File Upload.
inputs.label: Upload Session Id

inputs.comments: twb or twbx to indicate whether you have uploaded a workbook file (twb) or a packaged workbook file (twbx).
inputs.label: Workbook Type

inputs.comments: True to overwrite a workbook that has the same name, or false to fail if the specified workbook already exists.
inputs.label: Overwrite

inputs.comments: If false, the workbook publishing process runs as a synchronous process. If a workbook is very large, the process might time out before it finishes. If you set this value to true, the process runs asynchronously, and a job will start to perform the publishing process and return the job ID.
inputs.label: As Job

inputs.comments: If true, then the Tableau server will not check if a non-published connection of a workbook is reachable.
inputs.label: Skip Connection Check

inputs.comments: The twbx file to upload as binary data.
inputs.label: Workbook File Contents

display.label: Raw Request
display.description: Send a raw HTTP request to Tableau API

inputs.comments: Input the path only (/projects); the base URL is already included (https://{inputHostName}/api/{inputApiVersion}/sites/{siteId}). For example, to connect to https://{inputHostName}/api/{inputApiVersion}/sites/{siteId}/projects, enter only /projects in this field. Note: {inputHostName} is derived from the Host Name input in the connection configuration, {inputApiVersion} is based on the API Version input (default is 3.3), and {siteId} is automatically appended.
inputs.label: URL

inputs.comments: The HTTP method to use.
inputs.label: Method

inputs.comments: The HTTP body payload to send to the URL.
inputs.label: Data

inputs.comments: The Form Data to be sent as a multipart form upload.
inputs.label: Form Data

inputs.comments: File Data to be sent as a multipart form upload.
inputs.label: File Data

inputs.placeholder: The file name to apply to a file
inputs.comments: File names to apply to the file data inputs. Keys must match the file data keys above.
inputs.label: File Data File Names

inputs.comments: A list of query parameters to send with the request. This is the portion at the end of the URL similar to ?key1=value1&key2=value2.
inputs.label: Query Parameter

inputs.comments: A list of headers to send with the request.
inputs.label: Header

inputs.comments: The type of data you expect in the response. You can request json, text, or binary data.
inputs.label: Response Type

inputs.comments: The maximum time that a client will await a response to its request
inputs.label: Timeout

inputs.comments: Enabling this flag will log out the current request.
inputs.label: Debug Request

inputs.comments: The delay in milliseconds between retries.
inputs.label: Retry Delay (ms)

inputs.comments: If true, retries on all erroneous responses regardless of type.
inputs.label: Retry On All Errors

inputs.comments: The maximum number of retries to attempt.
inputs.label: Max Retry Count

inputs.comments: Specifies whether to use a pre-defined exponential backoff strategy for retries.
inputs.label: Use Exponential Backoff

inputs.comments: The version of the Tableau API to use
inputs.label: API Version

documentation.description:
[Tableau](https://www.tableau.com/) is an interactive data visualization software company focused on business intelligence.
The Tableau component allows you to manage your users, projects, workbooks, and connections through the Tableau Rest API.
